    "markdown": "## MRI Thigh Overview\n\n### What the scan does\n- \\*\\*Pinpoints\\*\\* the exact cause of thigh pain, swelling or weakness\n- \\*\\*Maps\\*\\* muscle tears, stress fractures, infections and tumors\n- \\*\\*Guides\\*\\* your doctor in choosing surgery, physiotherapy or medication\n### Key takeaways\n- \\*\\*Non-invasive\\*\\*: no needles, no incisions, no radiation\n- \\*\\*Detailed imaging\\*\\*: shows structures as small as 1–2 mm\n- \\*\\*Same-day reporting\\*\\*: most results ready within 2 hours\n\n## Risks & Limitations of MRI Thigh\n\n- \\*\\*Claustrophobia\\*\\*: our wide-bore scanner and music headphones reduce anxiety; open-MRI option available\n- \\*\\*Implants & metallic devices\\*\\*: pacemakers, cochlear implants, certain aneurysm clips may be contraindicated—inform staff beforehand\n- \\*\\*Contrast dye allergy\\*\\*: rare (<0.1%); discuss any previous reactions with our radiologist\n\n## Parameters Considered in MRI Thigh\n\n- \\*\\*Bone marrow signal\\*\\*—detects stress fractures, infection, cancer spread\n- \\*\\*Muscle & tendon integrity\\*\\*—grades hamstring, quadriceps or adductor tears\n- \\*\\*Ligament & cartilage condition\\*\\*—checks hip and knee ligaments\n- \\*\\*Soft-tissue masses or fluid collections\\*\\*—identifies hematomas, abscesses, tumors\n\n## Reasons for a Thigh MRI Scan\n\n- \\*\\*Accurate diagnosis of muscle tears\\*\\*—distinguishes partial vs complete ruptures\n- \\*\\*Detecting stress fractures not visible on X-ray\\*\\*—especially in runners\n- \\*\\*Evaluating extent of hematoma or abscess\\*\\*—guides drainage or antibiotics\n\n## Benefits of a Thigh MRI Scan\n\n- \\*\\*High-resolution images without radiation\\*\\*—safe for children and repeated scans\n- \\*\\*Guides surgical vs conservative treatment\\*\\*—prevents unnecessary surgery\n- \\*\\*Monitors healing progression\\*\\*—track recovery after physiotherapy or surgery\n\n## Conditions Diagnosed with MRI Thigh\n\n- \\*\\*Quadriceps or hamstring tears\\*\\*\n- \\*\\*Osteomyelitis\\*\\* (bone infection)\n- \\*\\*Soft-tissue sarcomas\\*\\*\n- \\*\\*Avascular necrosis of femur\\*\\* (bone death due to poor blood supply)\n\n## Preparation for MRI Thigh\n\n- \\*\\*Clothing and jewelry removal\\*\\*—wear metal-free cotton gown\n- \\*\\*Fasting instructions\\*\\*—skip breakfast only if contrast is planned\n- \\*\\*Informing staff\\*\\*—about pacemaker, pregnancy, or previous contrast reactions\n---\n## Pre-requisites\n- \\*\\*Doctor’s requisition form\\*\\*—carry printed or digital prescription\n- \\*\\*Recent creatinine report\\*\\*—within 4 weeks if contrast is planned\n---\n## Best Time to Take the MRI Thigh\n- \\*\\*Early morning slots\\*\\*—ideal for claustrophobic patients (less waiting)\n- \\*\\*Within 48–72 hrs post-injury\\*\\*—captures acute muscle edema and bleeding\n---\n## Eligibility\n- \\*\\*Adults and children\\*\\*—sedation available for kids under 6 years\n- \\*\\*Pregnancy considerations\\*\\*—defer unless urgent; no contrast in first trimester\n---\n## Procedure for Taking a MRI Thigh\n1. \\*\\*Check-in and screening questionnaire\\*\\*—metal check, medical history\n2. \\*\\*Positioning on the scanner table\\*\\*—lie on your back, thigh inside coil\n3. \\*\\*Typical scan duration\\*\\*—20 min (non-contrast) to 45 min (contrast)\n---\n## Caution Before Taking the Test\n- \\*\\*Remove all metallic objects\\*\\*—watches, rings, hairpins\n- \\*\\*Discuss kidney function\\*\\*—if eGFR <30, contrast may be withheld"
